d, Verenigd Koninkrijk","North Weald, Essex, England":"North Weald, Essex, England"},"en":{"Abt 1195–Bef 30 January 1250":"about 1195–before 30 January 1250","1195–1250":"1195–1250","1208–Female":"1208–Deceased","1245–Male":"1245–Deceased","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1168–1227":"1168–1227","–Female":"Deceased","Bef 1227":"before 1227","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1195":"1195","Bef 30 January 1250":"before 30 January 1250","1227":"1227","Abt 1195":"about 1195","um 1230":"about 1230","1168":"1168","1300":"1300","1245":"1245","before 1230":"before 1230","before 1195":"before 1195","1208":"1208","Raleigh, Essex, England":"Rayleigh, Essex, England","England":"England","North Weald Basset, Essex, England":"North Weald Bassett, Essex, England, United Kingdom","North Weald, Essex, England":"North Weald, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Essex","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from the county of Essex, whose name is from Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>Seaxe</i> ‘Saxons’. In England, the surname is now particularly common in Birmingham."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Hugh de Essex IV of North Weald was born about 1195, in North Weald Bassett, Essex, England, United Kingdom as the son of Hugh De Essex III and Mrs Hugh De Essex III. He married Christiane of Wiltshire before 1230, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died before 30 January 1250."},"et":{"Abt 1195–Bef 30 January 1250":"umbes 1195–enne 30. jaanuari 1250","1195–1250":"1195–1250","1208–Female":"1208–Surnud","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1168–1227":"1168–1227","–Female":"Surnud","Bef 1227":"enne 1227","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1195":"1195","Bef 30 January 1250":"enne 30. jaanuari 1250","1227":"1227","Abt 1195":"umbes 1195","um 1230":"umbes 1230","1168":"1168","1300":"1300","1245":"1245","before 1230":"enne 1230","before 1195":"enne 1195","1208":"1208","Raleigh, Essex, England":"Rayleigh, Essex, England","England":"England","North Weald Basset, Essex, Eng